        • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

          @mukyze- Don't talk rubbish. You could pay top players £1m a week and they wouldn't want to live in Bosnia. The only league outside of the top 4 which you could argue that a huge injection of money would (in practical terms) transform the league is France where there are potentially very big football teams based in nice places- Paris, Lyon, Marseille etc. We see that happening now with PSG. The exception is Monaco. Also, you seem to be disregarding how Bayern work inside of Germany. They essentially have every other team working as a feeder club. When you add that to a large fan-base (therefore revenue) and pulling power based on past success, being based in a nice city and guaranteeing being competitive in Europe then you realise they are every bit as rich as Man City and Chelsea. It's just that those 2 clubs overpay for players. Ditto with PSG & any small club who has been bought by a rich foreigner. That isn't the case with Man Utd, Liverpool & Arsenal who had success before money.

          @neumi17- No offence, but that's BS. There hasn't been a team in history who can just win when they want, against any team,- which is exactly what you're intimating. Even Alaba's fantastic strike came from failure to close him down in the middle of the park. Bayern are a better team but no way would they win 70% of the games between the 2, maybe 50% tops.

          Bayern obviously have one of the best squads in the world and a top manager, but that doesn't mean they have a divine right to destroy every team they face. After 11 rounds in the Bundesliga, Bayern are 5 points ahead of Dortmund in 2nd and 10 ahead of Wolfsburg in 3rd; that's roughly 50% more points/game between 1st and 3rd. The only other big league that's so one-sided is the French league, in all the others there are 3 points or less seperating the top 3 teams.
